In German, every noun has a grammatical gender (masculine, feminine, or neuter), and its article changes to match. It's not about biological gender, just a grammatical rule you get used to! Articles always stand before the noun.



ğŸ“š ğ€ğ«ğ­ğ¢ğœğ¥ğğ¬ ğ¢ğ§ ğ­ğ¡ğ ğğ¨ğ¦ğ¢ğ§ğšğ­ğ¢ğ¯ğ ğ‚ğšğ¬ğ (ğğšğ«ğ­ ğŸ - ğƒğğŸğ¢ğ§ğ¢ğ­ğ ğ€ğ«ğ­ğ¢ğœğ¥ğğ¬):

The Nominative case is basically for the subject of a sentence â€“ the person or thing doing the action, or the one being described. 



You can often figure out if something is in the Nominative by asking "Who?" (Wer?) or "What?" (Was?).

Here are the definite articles (like "the") you'll need for the Nominative case:

Masculine: der (e.g., der Mann - the man)

Feminine: die (e.g., die Frau - the woman)

Neuter: das (e.g., das Baby - the baby)

Plural (all genders): die (e.g., die MÃ¤nner, die Frauen, die Babys)



Let's see them in action:

Sabine ist ledig. (Sabine is single.) - Here, "Sabine" is the subject.

Das Haus ist groÃŸ. (The house is big.) - "Das Haus" is the subject.

Der Apfel ist rot. (The apple is red.) - "Der Apfel" is the subject.



